1. Core Product Vision

The notebook page becomes interactive mathematics.

You write normally.
The system understands the math structure and can:
	•	animate steps
	•	suggest hints
	•	correct mistakes
	•	reorganize the page
	•	explain reasoning
	•	save the thinking process

Instead of static notes, you get a living mathematical movie of your reasoning.

Think:

Paper + Whiteboard + Tutor + CAS + Replay Engine

⸻

2. User Experience

Main Canvas

The canvas is infinite notebook space.

Layers:
	1.	Ink Layer
	2.	Math Structure Layer
	3.	AI Annotation Layer
	4.	Animation Layer
	5.	Timeline Layer

Everything the user writes remains editable and reversible.

⸻

3. The Core Interaction

Step 1 — Write normally

User writes:

2x + 5 = 17

Step 2 — AI understands structure

Internally becomes:

Equation
  Left: 2x + 5
  Right: 17

Step 3 — AI offers actions

Small suggestions appear:
	•	Solve
	•	Hint
	•	Next step
	•	Explain

Step 4 — Animated transformation

Instead of jumping to the answer:

The page animates:

2x + 5 = 17
↓ subtract 5
2x = 12
↓ divide by 2
x = 6

Terms slide across the equation visually.

⸻

4. Magic Feature: Page Editing AI

The AI can edit the notebook itself.

Example:

User writes messy steps:

x^2 + 4x + 3

AI suggests:

“Factor?”

Tap.

Animation:

(x + 1)(x + 3)

Appears right where the original was written.

Original ink fades but remains available.

Undo always works.

⸻

5. Timeline of Thought

Every page stores a solution timeline.

[Problem Written]
↓
[Subtract 5]
↓
[Divide by 2]
↓
[Solution]

User can scrub back and replay.

This turns every solution into replayable learning.

⸻

6. Tutor System

The tutor never just dumps answers.

It operates in three levels:

Level 1 — Hint

Example:

“Try isolating x.”

Level 2 — Guided step

Animation shows operation but not result.

2x + 5 = 17
↓
2x = ?

Level 3 — Full solution

Complete derivation with explanation.

⸻

7. Animation Grammar

Math steps should have visual meaning.

Operation	Animation
Add/Subtract term	slide across equation
Multiply/Divide	scaling effect
Cancel terms	fade dissolve
Factorization	group contraction
Expansion	outward bloom
Substitution	morph replacement
Derivative	tangent line sweep
Integral	area fill

Animations are crucial because they show process.

⸻

